addr="jms-011P"
type="local">Forester 5.0 [TBA]</fr:link> › a URL scheme for tree addresses</fr:link> › what do we mean by “URL”?</fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Today, “URLs” are a mostly implementation-defined concept that can only be understood by looking at the source code of major web browsers; in the future, this may congeal into an actual standard but today is not that day (nor is tomorrow, if the state of the <fr:link
href="https://url.spec.whatwg.org/"
type="external"><fr:code>whatwg/url</fr:code> “living” [non-]standard</fr:link> is any indication). In the meanwhile, <fr:link
href="jms-005P.xml"
title="Forester"
addr="jms-005P"
type="local">Forester</fr:link> is implementing URLs in terms of <fr:link
href="jms-0119.xml"
title="Internationalized Resource Identifiers"
addr="jms-0119"
type="local">Internationalized Resource Identifiers (RFC 3987)</fr:link>; this standard improves on URIs by supporting unicode identifiers, which we need at the outset. It is best to think of <fr:link
href="jms-005P.xml"
title="Forester"
addr="jms-005P"
type="local">Forester</fr:link>’s adoption of <fr:link
href="jms-0119.xml"
title="Internationalized Resource Identifiers"
addr="jms-0119"
type="local">RFC 3987</fr:link> as provisional and subject to evolution as the Web continues to mature.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
